did.abstract: Service Employees International Union (SEIU) Local 585 was chartered in 1969 and represented health care employees, nonprofessional school district workers, and county civil servants in western Pennsylvania until 2002 when the local was disbanded. This collection contains information about Local 585 members and contract negotiations, typically organized by employer name.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection has been arranged into two series. The first is comprised of materials from the initial collection accession, which were arranged sometime in the 1990s. The second series contains all of the records added to the collection since 1982 and have not yet been more formally arranged.

bioghist.head: History
bioghist.p: Service Employees International Union (SEIU) Local 585 was chartered in 1969 after the passing of Pennsylvania Public Employees Act, Act 195, which established the right for public employees to organize and bargain collectively. The local represented three broad categories of workers in the Pittsburgh area: health care employees, nonprofessional school district workers, and county civil servants. In 1973, Rosemary Trump was elected president and under her tenure Local 585 grew to represent 15,000 workers throughout western Pennsylvania, becoming the second largest union in the region. While the number of employees in manufacturing unions declined, the number of employees in the service industry was on the rise and Local 585 was one of the few Pittsburgh area unions to increase its membership during the 1990s. In 1999, the local incorporated SEIU Local 29 which was also operating in Pittsburgh.

The 2000 election saw President Trump narrowly lose to newcomer Jim Neville, who was later removed by the international union under allegations that he violated the union's constitution. In March 2001, Local 585 was placed under the trusteeship of a member of SEIU District 925, who was then replaced that November by a trustee from Local 1199 Upstate in New York. In 2002, Local 585 was disbanded and its members were disbursed among three other industry specific SEIU locals: Local 668, government workers; Division 29/Local 47, commercial janitors and building maintenance services workers; and Local 1199P, health care workers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This collection contains contract negotiation information, grievances, member and seniority lists, and dues information from the various employers of members of Service Employees International Union Local 585. Also included are files regarding organization efforts in western Pennsylvania, as well as interunion rivalries and raids by other unions, such as the Teamsters, National Education Association and the Pennsylvania State Education Association. Executive board and membership meeting minutes from the 1970s are also present.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series includes files relating to chapters of SEIU Local 585 at educational institutions and represents the initial collection donation in 1982. The first portion of the series lists public school districts alphabetically by district name. The second portion lists colleges and universities alphabetically by school name. These files include information on organization efforts, contract negotiations and membership.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains all of the records donated to the collection after the initial accession in 1982. In addition to files regarding school districts, this series also includes information on municipal and county workers, as well as healthcare employees. Grievances, dues check-offs and contracts are present in this series. Information regarding SEIU Local 585, such as meeting minutes and newspaper clippings, are also included, as well as research materials and newsletters from other SEIU locals.
